Don&#39;t put commas until the end. The method [`str.join`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str.join) is made just for you. It is called on the separator (like `&#39;, &#39;`), and accepts an iterable of strings that you want to concentrate. For example:

```
def get_combination(decoded):
    def encode(x):
        if x &lt; 0:
            return f&#39;Left {abs(x)}&#39;
        return f&#39;Right {x}&#39;
    return &#39;, &#39;.join(encode(x) for x in decoded)
```

The last line could be rewritten using [`map`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#map) as

```
return &#39;, &#39;.join(map(encode, decoded))
```

If you want a really illegible one-liner (which I don&#39;t recommend, but python makes so easy to write):

```
&#39;, &#39;.join(f&#39;Left {abs(x)}&#39; if x &lt; 0 else f&#39;Right {x}&#39; for x in decoded)
```

or even (abusing f-strings to the max):

```
&#39;, &#39;.join(f&#39;{&quot;Left&quot; if x &lt; 0 else &quot;Right&quot;} {abs(x)}&#39; for x in decoded)
```

To stick to what your Computer Science 101 has already taught you, you can instead append `&quot;, &quot;` to `comb` at the beginning of the loop only if `comb` is not an empty string:

    def get_combination(decoded):
        comb = &quot;&quot;
        for elm in decoded:
            if comb != &quot;&quot;:
                comb += &quot;, &quot;
            if elm &gt;= 0: 
                comb += &quot;Right &quot;
            else:
                comb += &quot;Left &quot;
            comb += str(abs(elm))
        return comb

Or If you don&#39;t want to update your code you can use Strip method &lt;https://docs.python.org/2/library/string.html&gt;


    def get_combination(decoded):
    #(eg: get_combination([-2, 4, 2])
    #create an empty string
    comb = &quot;&quot;
    #For each elment in [decoded] check if the elm is &lt; 0 or elm is &gt;= 0
    for elm in decoded:
        if elm &gt;= 0: 
            #if the elm is greater than  0 add to the string comb
            # So the string will read (eg:Right 2) 
            comb += &quot;Right &quot; + str(abs(elm)) + &quot;, &quot;
        elif elm &lt; 0:
            #if the elm is less than 0 add to the string comb
            #So the string will read (eg: Left 4)
            comb += &quot;Left &quot;+ str(abs(elm)) + &quot;, &quot;
    return comb.rstrip(&quot;, &quot;)

