Typically you should follow the [CQRS pattern](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CQRS.html) when making changes with Firebase. In this approach you write any changes to the database, and then visualize those changes when the event fires back from Firebase. It sounds like that isn&#39;t possible for you, but I&#39;d still recommend considering it.

There is nothing built into Firebase to prevent the listener from firing for local events. But you can track each write that the local client starts (for example by keeping track of the push ID of each item that you write), and then filter those IDs out in your `on(&quot;child_` handlers.

For example to keep track of the keys:

    var newRef = ref.push(newData);
    var newKey = newRef.key;

And then in your listener:

    if (snapshot.key != newKey) {
      ...
    }

Of course if there can be multiple pending writes from the local client, you&#39;ll want to track those in an array.

