Given that you haven&#39;t learned about arrays, the idea behind your solution is quite ingenious, but there are some mistakes that would render your code dysfunctional.  

First off, there are many `while` loops that would either not execute or loop infinitely. It appears that you&#39;ve mixed up `while` loops with `if` statements. You can read more about the difference [here](https://www.quora.com/WHat-is-the-difference-between-an-if-and-a-while-loop).  

As both Andreas and Scary Wombat pointed out, there&#39;s a straggling `sc.nextInt();` that isn&#39;t assigned to anything. Delete that, since it will unintentionally drop inputs from the user.

With that in mind, here&#39;s my solution using your method.
```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class CountOccurence {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println(&quot;Enter the number&quot;);
        int num1 = sc.nextInt();
        System.out.println(&quot;Enter a list of positive numbers\nEnter -1 to indicate end:&quot;);
        int count = 0;
        int input = 0;
        while (input != -1) {
            input = sc.nextInt();
            if (input == num1) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        System.out.println(&quot;Your number occurs &quot; + count + &quot; times&quot;);
    }
}
```

I chose to print the occurances at the very end, since that&#39;s after the user types `-1`.

